\begin_layout Section
Task Definition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The objective of this thesis is narrowly focused:
 to develop and evaluate a unified 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

-field framework that (i) embeds both traversability-based and efficiency-based risks in a 3-D voxel map and (ii) exploits that representation for map fusion and high-level task allocation within a heterogeneous robot fleet.
 To preserve clarity and depth in this core contribution,
 several well-studied subsystems are declared out of scope and will be treated only through abstracted interfaces:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Low-level locomotion and flight control.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Detailed gait synthesis for legged robots,
 rotor dynamics for aerial vehicles,
 and thruster control for underwater platforms are not revisited.
 Each agent is modelled as a holonomic point mass whose motion is limited only by simple kinematic bounds (maximum speed,
 slope tolerance,
 climb rate).
 These bounds enter the framework through locomotion-specific weight factors in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

-field,
 but no internal controller is designed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
On-board state estimation and SLAM back-ends.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Visual-inertial odometry,
 Doppler velocity logs,
 and other estimation pipelines vary widely across platforms and could obscure the main argument.
 In simulation we assume drift-free odometry;
 when desirable,
 bounded Gaussian noise is injected to emulate localisation uncertainty.
 The emphasis remains on how risk maps influence decision-making,
 not on how robot poses are derived.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Communication protocol engineering.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Channel-level issues such as modulation,
 bandwidth management,
 latency,
 and acoustic packet loss are outside the present scope.
 Connectivity is abstracted as a binary or probabilistic variable that feeds the efficiency-risk component λ_C;
 no bespoke networking stack is proposed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fine-grained energy management.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hardware-level power scheduling (CPU throttling,
 sensor duty cycling) requires platform-specific models.
 Here battery depletion is approximated by a terrain-conditioned drain rate aggregated into λ_B,
 sufficient for strategic planning but not for component-level optimisation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Reactive inter-robot collision avoidance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Local avoidance has been addressed extensively in the literature (e.g.,
 ORCA,
 reciprocal velocity obstacles).
 We assume that once way-points are issued,
 standard reflexive schemes ensure short-range safety;
 the high-level planner merely avoids allocating overlapping target volumes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Multimodal perception fusion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Raw sensor integration (RGB-D,
 thermal,
 radar) is not re-implemented.
 Individual robots are assumed to provide locally consistent OctoMaps generated by existing SLAM packages;
 our contribution begins at the stage of octree alignment and global fusion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Problem Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given an initially unknown three-dimensional environment,
 estimate a 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

-field that quantifies,
 for every voxel,
 the compounded likelihood of mission-critical failure (physical or efficiency-related).
 Use this field both to merge local OctoMaps into a coherent global model and to assign way-points or tasks to heterogeneous robots so that the expected cumulative risk of the mission is minimised.
\end_layout

